[{"id":41705,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cb9ce9a-72ba-4b3f-8f81-e25c10734098-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 139px;\" /></p><p>Emf produced is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>L</mi><mo>&#8869;</mo></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8869;</mo></msub></math></p><p>We know&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>, so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41716,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["(C) and&nbsp;(E) only","(B) and&nbsp;(D) only","(A) and&nbsp;(B) only","(B) and (C) only"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Statement (C) is correct because, the magnetic field outside the toroid is zero and they form closed loops inside the toroid itself.</p><p>Statement (E) is correct because we know that super conductors are materials inside which the net magnetic field is always zero and they are perfect diamagnetic.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#967;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p>For superconductors.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41688,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$8 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}$","$4 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}$","Zero","$16 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"At stable equilibrium\n$\\mathrm{U}=-\\mathrm{mB} \\cos 0^{\\circ}=-\\mathrm{mB}$<br />At unstable equilibrium\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{U}=-\\mathrm{mB} \\cos 180^{\\circ}=+\\mathrm{mB} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{W}=\\Delta \\mathrm{U} \\\\\n& \\text { W.D. }=2 \\mathrm{mB} \\\\\n& =2(0.5) 8 \\times 10^{-2}=8 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41693,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>It is given that&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>The permeability is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math>.</p><p>The magnetic field is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p><p>Hence, percentage increase in magnetic field is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>B</mi></mstyle><mn>0</mn></msub></mstyle><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41696,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The magnetic intensity is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi></math></p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, it can be written</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi></math></p><p>The data given is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>l</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">=</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn></math></p><p>Using the relation,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>N</mi><mi>l</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi></math>, the value of the current is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>H</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41712,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Both Statement I and Statement II are true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I&nbsp;is false but Statement II is true."],"answer":0,"solution":"As temperature increases, domains disintegrate so ferromagnetism decreases and above curie temperature it become paramagnet.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41736,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;for transformers and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math></p><p>for electric generators.</p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;for electromagnets and transformers.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;for electric generators and transformers.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;for electromagnets and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> for electric generators."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>As we know that, area of&nbsp;Hysteresis loop represents the net loss of energy&nbsp;by the material per unit volume,taken over complete cycle.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d8351c41-e7db-42cd-8a5f-6d86920cd3e7-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 223px;\" /><br />Graph <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;is hard ferromagnetic material substance as the area of the loop is more, hence the hysteresis loss will be more and thus the value of coercivity will be high which are best suited to use as Permanent Magnet<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f2d12aad-bfdc-4da9-a7ab-a04b96dbc02a-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 218px;\" /><br />Graph <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;is graph of soft ferromagnetic material substance as the area of the loop is less and hence the hysterisis loss will be less which is required condition for transformer. And the value of coercivity will be low too.</p><p>Hence this material are best suited to use as Electromagnets and Transformer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41745,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/JymYEBFVByxPLC0DsJQVPN9k3YyY8U7lZAg3KOWlWH8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RyE4oqQ1bzjHdI33B6Ax2aer1KH6ypFPTYvDRS35e7M.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0DOL6lSHuw9VixnyCMCoH05MUu8bHuFLsrLuvnJ82uk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rtl83mKH9lI7uih9jCT2w0BIcuVwd5mGDMnmGKqUUuE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"If magnetic field is perpendicular and into the plane of the paper, it is represented by cross $\\otimes$ and if the direction of the magnetic field is perpendicular out of the plane of the paper it is represented by dot $\\odot$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41728,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$3.3 \\times 10^{-2}$","$4.3 \\times 10^{-2}$","$2.3 \\times 10^{-2}$","$3.3 \\times 10^{-4}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Magnetic susceptibility,\r\n\r\n$\\chi=\\frac{\\mathrm{I}}{\\mathrm{H}}$\r\n\r\nwhere, $\\mathrm{I}=\\frac{\\text { Magnetic moment }}{\\text { Volume }}=\\frac{20 \\times 10^{-6}}{10^{-6}}=20 \\mathrm{~N} / \\mathrm{m}^{2}$\r\n\r\nNow , $\\chi=\\frac{20}{60 \\times 10^{3}}=\\frac{1}{3} \\times 10^{-3}=3.3 \\times 10^{-4}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41754,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~W}$","W","$\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\mathrm{~W}$","$2 \\mathrm{~W}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\tau=(\\mathrm{H}) \\tan 60^{\\circ} \\quad=\\mathrm{W} \\cdot \\sqrt{3}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":41739,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>&#8800;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi>B</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"In diamagnetic material, the magnetic field strength decreases. So, in a perfect diamagnetic,&nbsp;it has to be zero.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41735,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>40&nbsp;</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>135</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi></math> with left side of pilot at higher voltage","<math><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mi> </mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>120</mn><mi> </mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi></math>  with right side of pilot at higher voltage","<math><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mi> </mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>135</mn><mi> </mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi></math>  with right side of pilot at high voltage","<math><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>120</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi></math> with left side of pilot at higher voltage"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0ac2638f-7bb0-45f3-bc47-014ffe6f7668-image.png\" style=\"width: 257px; height: 200px;\" /><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>V</mtext> <mtext>B</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>H</mn> </msub> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mn>4</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>H</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>B cos</mtext> <mi>&#952;, ....</mi> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>H</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <msqrt> <mn>5</mn> </msqrt> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>5</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>v</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>5</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mtext>T</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>V</mtext> <mtext>B</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <msqrt> <mn>5</mn> </msqrt> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>5</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mn>4</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>V</mtext> <mtext>B</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>44.6</mtext> <mo>mV</mo> <mo>=</mo> <mn>4</mn> <mn>5</mn> <mtext>mV</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>V</mtext> <mtext>w</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mrow> <mtext>v</mtext></mrow></msub> <mi>&#8467;</mi> <mtext>V</mtext>&#160;</mrow></math><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mn>10</mn> </mrow> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> <mo>&#215;</mo><msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>5</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>240</mn> </mrow></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <mn>0</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>V</mtext> <mtext>w</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <mn>0</mn> <mo>mV</mo> </mrow> </math><br /><br />(left side at fighter voltage)<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de9311e2-77df-478a-a1bd-33d1ba39ebe8-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 230px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41708,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["low coercivity and high retentivity.","low coercivity and low permeability.","high permeability and low retentivity.","high permeability and high retentivity."],"answer":2,"solution":"Electromagnets are made of soft iron because of its high permeability and low retentivity. High permeability&nbsp;means that the core provides complete linkage of magnetic flux of the primary coil to the secondary coil.&nbsp;&nbsp;The determination of the magnetism left in the material after the removal of the magnetizing field is known as retentivity. The required condition for the operation of electromagnets is the fast reversal of polarity, so high retentivity is undesirable. So, soft iron core has high permeability and low retentivity.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41681,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\frac{6}{5} \\times 10^{-3} \\%$","$\\frac{5}{6} \\times 10^{-5} \\%$","$\\frac{5}{6} \\times 10^{-4} \\%$","$\\frac{5}{3} \\times 10^{-5} \\%$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\% \\text { change in } B=\\frac{B_{\\text {new }}-B_{\\text {old }}}{B_{\\text {old }}} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\frac{\\mu \\mathrm{ni}-\\mu_0 \\mathrm{ni}}{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{ni}} \\times 100 \\%=\\frac{\\left(\\mu-\\mu_0\\right)}{\\mu_0} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\frac{\\left(\\mu_0 \\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}-\\mu_0\\right)}{\\mu_0} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\left(\\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}-1\\right) \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\chi_{\\mathrm{n}} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =1.2 \\times 10^{-3} \\%\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41704,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Magnetic field inside the material in solenoid is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#967;</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi></math>&nbsp;is current.</p><p>Now, magnetic field with air as medium&nbsp;inside solenoid is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi></math>.</p><p>So, fractional increase is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><mi>B</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>&#967;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41684,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$4 \\%$","$15 \\%$","$5 \\%$","$10 \\%$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/SES2iVZmAuOyfB9z77qA77SZx-xh77PPMKzRKnntIHg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nMagnetic field at $P, B=\\frac{\\mu_0}{4 \\pi} \\frac{m(2 l)}{r^3}$, where $m$ is the pole strength\n$\\begin{aligned}\n\\Rightarrow\\left(\\frac{\\Delta B}{B} \\times 100\\right) & =\\left(\\frac{\\Delta l}{l}\\right) \\times 100+3\\left|\\frac{\\Delta r}{r}\\right| \\times 100 \\\\\n& =1 \\%+3 \\%=4 \\%\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41697,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> is not correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is correct","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> is correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is not correct","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> are correct and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math>","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> are correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is NOT the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>A coil surrounding a magnetic core&nbsp;having high permeability and low&nbsp;retentivity,&nbsp;through which an electric current is&nbsp;fed&nbsp;to&nbsp;magnetise&nbsp;the&nbsp;core&nbsp;is&nbsp;what&nbsp;makes&nbsp;up&nbsp;an&nbsp;electromagnet. Wherever controllable magnets are needed, as in devices where the magnetic flux needs to be adjusted, reversed, or turned on and off, an electromagnet is used.</p><p>Hence, both <strong>A</strong> and <strong>R</strong> are correct and <strong>R</strong> is the correct explanation of <strong>A</strong>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41680,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["Both $(\\mathrm{A})$ and $(\\mathrm{R})$ are correct but $(\\mathrm{R})$ is not the correct explanation of (A)","(A) is correct but $(\\mathrm{R})$ is not correct","Both $(\\mathrm{A})$ and $(\\mathrm{R})$ are correct and $(\\mathrm{R})$ is the correct explanation of (A)","(A) is not correct but ( $\\mathrm{R}$) is correct"],"answer":2,"solution":"Both statements are correct and reason is also the correct explanation of assertion.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41725,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math><mn>3.6</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.8</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.2</mn></math>","<math><mn>0.7</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> be the respective oscillation frequencies respectively for&nbsp;<math><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math> and <math><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;dip. Then,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mi>I</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mi>I</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>30</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mn>40</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>900</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>1600</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.688</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0.7</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41746,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.50</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.80</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.56</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0010402_AnsExp4_1.jpg\" /><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>net</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>H</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math><mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>μ</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>M</mtext> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>x</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>μ</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>M</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>x</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <msub><mtext>B</mtext> <mtext>H</mtext> </msub></mrow></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mrow><mo>{</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow> </msup> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>1.2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mo>}</mo></mrow></mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>0.1</mn></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo><mn>3.6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>2.56</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mtext>&nbsp;Wb</mtext> <mo>/</mo> <msup> <mtext>m</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41755,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["are from north-pole to south-pole of the magnet","do not exist","depend upon the area of cross-section of the bar magnet","are from south-pole to north-pole of the magnet"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":41689,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Component of the magnetic field perpendicular to the plane of fan blades, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>sin</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>Angular frequency, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>1200</mn><mo> </mo><mi>rad</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo> </mo><mi>rad</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Therefore, induced EMF</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ε</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mi>ω</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><mn>40</mn><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41713,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["True dip is not mathematically related to apparent dip.","True dip is less than apparent dip.","True dip is always greater than the apparent dip.","True dip is always equal to apparent dip."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>If&nbsp;the apparent dip circle is at an angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>&nbsp;with true dip circle then,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11ac7fc1-12b6-4947-bd46-b6fc87302962-D780.png\" style=\"width: 284px; height: 401px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>tan</mi><mfenced><mi>&#981;</mi></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></math></p><p>Therefore, apparent dip angle is greater than true dip angle.</p><p>Hence, true dip <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is less than apparent dip&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msup><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41685,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2Ca9ebgPH7LOb-A4W4wP6EN_LTd7KUz1YSm2SuvLn-E.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{H}_{\\mathrm{c}}=\\frac{\\mu_{\\mathrm{o}} \\mathrm{ni}}{\\mu_{\\mathrm{o}}} \\\\ & 5 \\times 10^3=\\frac{150}{30} \\times 100 \\times \\mathrm{i} \\\\ & \\frac{50}{5}=\\mathrm{i} \\\\ & \\mathrm{I}=10\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41711,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>H</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi>H</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>22</mn><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41691,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The formula for time period is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>M</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p>Let</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>The ratio of the time periods is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>30</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>2</mn></mstyle></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><msqrt><mn>243</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41723,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>","Zero","much large than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and parallel to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>","much large than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mfenced></math>&nbsp;but opposite to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"When magnetic field is applied diamagnetic substance produces magnetic field in opposite direction so net magnetic field will be zero.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41701,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given here, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;and apparent value of dip, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math> is horizontal component of earth&#39;s magnetic field in magnetic meridian, then&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>H</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;be component of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math>&nbsp;at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;to magnetic meridian, then&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>H</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>tan</mi><msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus, the actual value of the angle of dip is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>tan</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msqrt><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41699,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b418d024-091f-4ee8-9b8b-c6fdff72575f-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 57px;\" /></p><p>Given here:</p><p>The vertical component of the earths magnetic field&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp;and angle of dip&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>37</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p>For vertical component,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#948;</mi></math></p><p>Putting the values, we have&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Earth&#39;s magnetic field at that place as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41677,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\dfrac{25}{\\pi}$","$\\dfrac{1}{16\\pi}$","$\\dfrac{1}{\\pi}$","$\\dfrac{1}{4\\pi}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The magnetic field $B$ inside the solenoid is related to the magnetic intensity $H$ by the formula:<br><br>$B = \\mu H = \\mu_0 \\mu_r H$<br><br>Rearranging for $H$, we get:<br><br>$H = \\dfrac{B}{\\mu_0 \\mu_r}$<br><br>Substituting the given values ($B = 1.0$ T, $\\mu_r = 400$, and $\\mu_0 = 4\\pi \\times 10^{-7}$ T m/A):<br><br>$H = \\dfrac{1.0}{4\\pi \\times 10^{-7} \\times 400}$<br><br>$H = \\dfrac{1.0}{1600\\pi \\times 10^{-7}}$<br><br>$H = \\dfrac{1}{16\\pi \\times 10^{-5}}$<br><br>$H = \\dfrac{1}{16\\pi} \\times 10^5$ A/m<br><br>Comparing this with the given expression $H = \\alpha \\times 10^5$, we find:<br><br>$\\alpha = \\dfrac{1}{16\\pi}$<br><br>Answer: $\\dfrac{1}{16\\pi}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null}]